Consider what I wrote above about the possessive. Mufasa's is not the same as Mufasa, right? And that's exactly how cases work. Syna (the genetive case of son, and thus and equivalent of your possessive son's) is *not* the same as "syn" (son), period. And it's like that with all the other cases, too.

The clue is wrong, even if so many here can't see it. The fact you translate both DIES and DIEM as "day" does not mean DIEM meant "day" in Ancient Rome, just as the simple fact you would translate the vocative Warszawo! as Warsaw! does not mean Warszawo is Warsaw in modern Poland. In other words, the exact way you translate something into English does not change the rules of the language you are translating from, and when the clue is asking for the original language, the answer should conform to *that* language's rules.

